 be recuperated from its status as the bad object of queer politics to better understand how legal discourses open up sites for identification across identity categories and enable political activities that escape the analytics of heteronormativity and homonationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aTransgender peoplexCivil rights. 0aTransgender peoplexIdentity. 0aTransgender peoplexPolitical activity. 0aTransgender people; Civil rights. 0aTransgender people; Identity. 0aTransgender people; Political activity. 0aTranssexualsxCivil rights. 0aTranssexualsxPolitical activity. 0aTranssexuals; Civil rights. 0aTranssexuals; Political activity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978147983214940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479832149.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479826872423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479826872/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK